# LogicN v1 Formal Grammar (EBNF)

<!-- profile: v1-current -->

## Status

```text
Spec status: v1 canonical grammar
Implementation status: parser is live; guarded flow, route, fn, intent,
compute target, and expression forms are implemented (Phases 7–51 complete).
```

This grammar defines the intended v1 surface syntax for the Canonical Example
Corpus. It is more complete than the current TypeScript prototype parser.

## Lexical Conventions

```ebnf
letter              = "A".."Z" | "a".."z" | "_" ;
digit               = "0".."9" ;
identifier          = letter , { letter | digit } ;
type_identifier     = "A".."Z" , { letter | digit } ;
enum_case           = type_identifier ;

integer_literal     = digit , { digit } ;
decimal_literal     = digit , { digit } , "." , digit , { digit } ;
string_literal      = '"' , { character | escape_sequence } , '"' ;
char_literal        = "'" , character , "'" ;
bool_literal        = "true" | "false" ;

literal             = decimal_literal
                    | integer_literal
                    | string_literal
                    | char_literal
                    | bool_literal ;

comment             = line_comment | doc_comment ;
line_comment        = "//" , { character } ;
doc_comment         = "///" , { character } ;
```

Whitespace and comments separate tokens and are otherwise insignificant except
where examples use newlines for readability.

## Compilation Unit

```ebnf
compilation_unit    = { top_level_item } ;

top_level_item      = type_decl
                    | record_decl
                    | enum_decl
                    | flow_decl
                    | route_decl
                    | import_decl ;

import_decl         = "import" , qualified_name , [ "as" , identifier ] ;
```

`fn` is intentionally absent from `top_level_item`; helper functions may only
appear inside a flow body.

## Types

```ebnf
type_decl           = "type" , type_identifier , ( type_alias | type_body ) ;
record_decl         = "record" , type_identifier , type_body ;

type_alias          = "=" , type_ref ;
type_body           = "{" , { field_decl } , "}" ;
field_decl          = identifier , ":" , type_ref ;

type_ref            = [ type_governance_qualifier ] , primary_type_ref ,
                      { type_state_qualifier } ;

type_governance_qualifier
                    = "protected" | "redacted" ;

primary_type_ref    = type_identifier , [ generic_args ]
                    | "Brand" , "<" , type_ref , "," , string_literal , ">"
                    | "(" , type_ref , ")" ;

generic_args        = "<" , type_ref , { "," , type_ref } , ">" ;

type_state_qualifier
                    = "unsafe" | "safe" | "validated" | "unvalidated"
                    | "secure" | "secret" ;
```

`protected` and `redacted` are prefix governance qualifiers. `String unsafe` is
a postfix value-state type annotation. `Email protected` and `Email redacted`
are invalid.

## Enums, Option, Result, and Match

```ebnf
enum_decl           = "enum" , type_identifier , "{" ,
                      [ enum_case_list ] , "}" ;

enum_case_list      = enum_case , { enum_separator , enum_case } ,
                      [ enum_separator ] ;
enum_separator      = "," | newline ;

match_expr          = "match" , expression , "{" , { match_arm } , "}" ;
match_arm           = ( when_guard_arm | pattern ) , "=>" , arm_body , [ "," ] ;

(* Phase 41 — when-guard arms *)
when_guard_arm      = "when" , expression ;
(* 'when expression => ...' allows arbitrary boolean guards in a match arm.
   Example: when score >= 90 => return "critical"
   The guard expression may reference the match subject or any in-scope binding. *)

arm_body            = expression | statement ;

pattern             = "_"
                    | enum_case
                    | qualified_enum_case
                    | option_pattern
                    | result_pattern
                    | integer_literal
                    | string_literal
                    | literal
                    | identifier ;
(* integer_literal and string_literal are listed explicitly to document that
   integer and string match arms are valid. Example: 200 => return "ok"
   They are subsumed by the 'literal' alternative but called out for clarity. *)

qualified_enum_case = type_identifier , "." , enum_case ;
option_pattern      = "Some" , "(" , pattern , ")" | "None" ;
result_pattern      = "Ok" , "(" , pattern , ")" | "Err" , "(" , pattern , ")" ;
```

`Option<T>` and `Result<T, E>` are standard generic types. Matches over enums,
`Option`, and `Result` must be exhaustive unless a wildcard arm is accepted by
policy. General exhaustiveness diagnostics use `LLN-MATCH-*`; type-level
match diagnostics may also report `LLN-TYPE-021`.

## Flow Declarations

```ebnf
flow_decl           = [ flow_qualifier ] , "flow" , identifier ,
                      "(" , [ param_list ] , ")" , ( "->" | ":" ) , type_ref ,
                      { flow_clause } , block ;
(* Both '->' and ':' are accepted as return-type separators; no diagnostic
   is emitted for either. Formatters normalise to '->'. *)

flow_qualifier      = "pure" | "guarded" | "secure" ;
(* Top-level qualifiers 'safe flow', 'guard flow', and 'unsafe flow' are
   REMOVED. They emit LLN-SYNTAX-LEGACY-002 (warning) if encountered.
   Use 'pure', 'guarded', or 'secure' instead. *)

param_list          = param , { "," , param } ;
param               = [ "readonly" ] , identifier , ":" , type_ref ;

flow_clause         = effects_clause
                    | intent_clause
                    | compute_target_block
                    | contract_block ;

(* Phase 41 — inline contract style
   The contract block may appear as the FIRST item inside the flow body '{}' instead
   of between the signature and the body. Both placements are valid.

   Traditional (external) style:
     pure flow foo(x: Int) -> String
     contract { intent { "..." } }
     { ... body ... }

   Modern (inline) style — preferred for compact flows:
     pure flow foo(x: Int) : String {
       contract { intent { "..." } }
       ... body ...
     }

   The inline form is syntactically a contract_block statement inside the block.
   Formatters may normalise to either style; the inline style is the modern preferred form. *)

contract_block      = "contract" , "{" ,
                      { contract_clause } ,
                      "}" ;

contract_clause     = contract_types
                    | contract_intent
                    | contract_request
                    | contract_response
                    | contract_context
                    | contract_model
                    | contract_effects
                    | contract_economics
                    | contract_timeouts
                    | contract_retries
                    | contract_limits
                    | contract_privacy
                    | contract_errors
                    | contract_rules
                    | contract_observability
                    | contract_events
                    | contract_audit
                    | contract_governance
                    | contract_targets
                    | contract_examples ;

(* Canonical 17-section contract order (formatters must emit in this order):
   types, intent, request, response, context, model, effects,
   economics, timeouts, retries, limits, privacy, errors, rules,
   observability, events, audit *)

contract_types      = "types" , "{" ,
                      { type_decl } ,
                      "}" ;

contract_intent     = "intent" , "{" , string_literal , "}" ;

contract_events     = "events" , "{" ,
                      { "emits" , identifier } ,
                      "}" ;

contract_request    = "request" , "{" ,
                      [ "accepts" , type_ref ] ,
                      [ "params" , "{" , { field_decl } , "}" ] ,
                      [ "requires" , "{" , { identifier } , "}" ] ,
                      "}" ;

contract_response   = "response" , "{" ,
                      [ "returns" , type_ref ] ,
                      [ "exposes" , "{" , { identifier } , "}" ] ,
                      [ "denies" , "{" , { identifier } , "}" ] ,
                      "}" ;

contract_context    = "context" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_model      = "model" , "{" ,
                      [ "uses" , type_ref ] ,
                      [ "reads" , type_ref ] ,
                      "}" ;

contract_effects    = "effects" , "{" , { effect_name } , "}" ;
(* Phase 41 — effects {} is optional for pure flows.
   Omitting effects {} entirely means the flow declares no side-effects (pure).
   An explicit empty 'effects {}' is equivalent to omission.
   For guarded and secure flows, effects {} MUST be present if any effects are observed. *)

contract_economics  = "economics" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_rules      = "rules" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_audit      = "audit" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_governance = "governance" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_targets    = "targets" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_examples   = "examples" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_errors     = "errors" , "{" ,
                      [ "returns" , "{" , { qualified_name } , "}" ] ,
                      [ "expose"  , "{" , { identifier } , "}" ] ,
                      [ "redact"  , "{" , { identifier } , "}" ] ,
                      [ "audit"   , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ] ,
                      { "map" , qualified_name , "to" , qualified_name } ,
                      "}" ;

contract_timeouts   = "timeouts" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_retries    = "retries" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_limits     = "limits" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_privacy    = "privacy" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

contract_observability = "observability" , "{" , { any_token } , "}" ;

event_decl          = "event" , identifier ;

emit_stmt           = "emit" , identifier ;

effects_clause      = [ "with" ] , "effects" , "[" ,
                      [ effect_name , { "," , effect_name } ] , "]" ;
(* REMOVED — LLN-SYNTAX-LEGACY-001 (hard error)
   'with effects [...]' is no longer valid syntax. The parser emits a hard
   error when this form is encountered. The canonical form is:
     contract { effects { database.read, audit.write } }
   See: contract_effects production above. *)

effect_name         = identifier , "." , identifier ,
                      { "." , identifier } ;

intent_clause       = "intent" , string_literal ;
```

`with effects [...]` is a **hard error** (LLN-SYNTAX-LEGACY-001). All effect
declarations must use `contract { effects {} }`. The `effects_clause` production
above is retained in the grammar for documentation purposes only and is not
parsed by the v1 parser.

Rules:

- `pure flow` must not declare or observe effects.
- `guarded flow` must declare every effect it uses, including effects used by
  local `fn` helpers.
- `secure flow` is the trust-boundary form and may declare effects, intent,
  governance, authority, and audit requirements.

## Local fn

```ebnf
fn_decl             = "fn" , identifier , "(" , [ param_list ] , ")" ,
                      ( "->" | ":" ) , type_ref , block ;
```

`fn_decl` is valid only as a `statement` inside a flow body. It cannot appear
at top level, cannot declare `effects`, cannot request authority, is always
synchronous, and cannot spawn tasks.

## Routes

```ebnf
route_decl          = "route" , route_method , string_literal , "{" ,
                      route_request ,
                      route_response ,
                      route_flow ,
                      "}" ;

route_method        = "GET" | "POST" | "PUT" | "PATCH" | "DELETE"
                    | "HEAD" | "OPTIONS" | identifier ;

route_request       = "request" , type_ref ;
route_response      = "response" , type_ref ;
route_flow          = "flow" , identifier ;
```

Routes contain no business logic. They expose an external entry point and
delegate entirely to a named flow.

## Compute Target Blocks

```ebnf
compute_target_block
                    = "compute" , "target" , compute_target_selector ,
                      "{" , { compute_target_clause } , "}" ;

compute_target_selector
                    = "best" | compute_target_name ;

compute_target_clause
                    = "prefer" , "[" , target_list , "]"
                    | "deny" , "[" , deny_list , "]"
                    | "fallback" , compute_target_name ;

target_list         = compute_target_name , { "," , compute_target_name } ;
deny_list           = deny_item , { "," , deny_item } ;

compute_target_name = "cpu" | "gpu" | "npu" | "wasm" | "photonic"
                    | "ai_accelerator" | identifier ;

deny_item           = qualified_name | identifier ;
```

Compute target blocks constrain planning. They must not change security,
governance, authority, effects, validation, redaction, or program meaning.

## Blocks and Statements

```ebnf
block               = "{" , { statement } , "}" ;

statement           = binding_stmt
                    | assignment_stmt
                    | return_stmt
                    | if_stmt
                    | match_stmt
                    | fn_decl
                    | expression_stmt ;

binding_stmt        = binding_prefix , identifier ,
                      [ ":" , type_ref ] , "=" , expression ;

binding_prefix      = "let"
                    | "mut"
                    | "readonly"
                    | "unsafe" , ( "let" | "mut" )
                    | "safe" , "mut" ;

assignment_stmt     = assignable , "=" , expression ;
return_stmt         = "return" , expression ;

if_stmt             = "if" , expression , block , [ "else" , block ] ;
(* Phase 41 — 'else if' is a HARD ERROR (LLN-SYNTAX-010). The grammar intentionally
   does not allow 'else if_stmt' (recursive else-if chains). The 'else' arm accepts
   only a plain block. Use 'match' for multi-branch conditions, or write sequential
   'if' statements. Example:

     // CORRECT — sequential if (binary decision):
     if age >= 18 {
       return true
     }
     return false

     // CORRECT — match for multi-branch:
     match score {
       when score >= 90 => return "critical"
       when score >= 70 => return "high"
       _               => return "low"
     }

     // ERROR LLN-SYNTAX-010 — else if is not valid LogicN:
     // if a { ... } else if b { ... }
*)
match_stmt          = match_expr ;
expression_stmt     = expression ;

assignable          = identifier , { "." , identifier | "[" , expression , "]" } ;
```

`unsafe let` marks boundary-origin data. `safe mut` is the controlled upgrade
form after an approved validation/decode gate.

## Expressions and Operators

The expression grammar follows the precedence table in
`docs/Knowledge-Bases/operator-precedence.md`.

```ebnf
expression          = logical_or ;

logical_or          = logical_and , { "||" , logical_and } ;
logical_and         = equality , { "&&" , equality } ;
equality            = comparison , { ( "==" | "!=" ) , comparison } ;
comparison          = additive , { ( "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">=" ) , additive } ;
additive            = multiplicative , { ( "+" | "-" ) , multiplicative } ;
multiplicative      = unary , { ( "*" | "/" | "%" ) , unary } ;
unary               = ( "!" | "-" ) , unary | postfix ;
postfix             = primary , { member_access | call_suffix
                                  | index_suffix | error_propagation } ;

member_access       = "." , identifier ;
call_suffix         = "(" , [ argument_list ] , ")" ;
index_suffix        = "[" , expression , "]" ;
error_propagation   = "?" ;

primary             = literal
                    | identifier
                    | qualified_name
                    | object_literal
                    | list_literal
                    | match_expr
                    | "(" , expression , ")" ;

argument_list       = expression , { "," , expression } ;
qualified_name      = identifier , { "." , identifier } ;

object_literal      = "{" , [ object_field , { "," , object_field } ] ,
                      [ "," ] , "}" ;
object_field        = identifier , ":" , expression ;

list_literal        = "[" , [ expression , { "," , expression } ] ,
                      [ "," ] , "]" ;
```

Operator precedence, tightest last:

| Level | Operators | Associativity |
|---|---|---|
| 10 | `||` | left |
| 20 | `&&` | left |
| 30 | `==` `!=` | left |
| 40 | `<` `<=` `>` `>=` | left |
| 50 | `+` `-` | left |
| 60 | `*` `/` `%` | left |
| 70 | prefix `!` `-` | right |
| 80 | `.` `()` `[]` postfix `?` | left/postfix |

`?` is postfix error propagation. It binds tighter than all infix operators:
`validate.email(raw)? || fallback` parses as `(validate.email(raw)?) || fallback`.

## Governance, Authority, and Policy Blocks

These blocks appear inside `secure flow` bodies and at top-level (governance,
api declarations). They are Phase 7B / 8 semantics; the parser currently
handles them as generic blocks (see `parseGenericBlock` in parser.ts).

```ebnf
governance_decl     = "governance" , identifier , "{" , { governance_clause } , "}" ;

authority_block     = "authority" , authority_action , [ authority_target ] ,
                      "{" , { authority_clause } , "}" ;

authority_action    = "share" | "delegate" | "grant" | identifier ;
authority_target    = qualified_name ;

authority_clause    = "reason" , string_literal
                    | "require" , effect_name
                    | "expires" , string_literal
                    | "audit" , ( "required" | "optional" ) ;

policy_block        = "policy" , "{" , { policy_clause } , "}" ;

policy_clause       = "purpose" , string_literal
                    | "allow" , type_ref , "to" , string_literal
                    | "deny" , type_ref
                    | "require" , effect_name ;

runtime_block       = "runtime" , ( "adaptive" | "deterministic" ) ,
                      [ "{" , { runtime_clause } , "}" ] ;

runtime_clause      = "observe" , identifier
                    | "learn" , "from" , identifier
                    | "optimise" , "[" , identifier_list , "]"
                    | "preserve" , "[" , identifier_list , "]" ;

identifier_list     = identifier , { "," , identifier } ;
```

The `authority` block grants temporary authority for data sharing outside
the normal governed boundary. It must include a `reason` and typically
requires `audit.write` to be declared on the enclosing flow.

The `policy` block constrains what the flow may do with specific data
categories. `purpose` is a machine-readable intent tag the governance
verifier checks against observed behaviour.

The `runtime` block configures the Adaptive Runtime profile for this
flow's execution. `runtime deterministic` disables all adaptive optimisation.

---

## Explicitly Excluded From v1

```text
safe flow, unsafe flow, guard flow  — emit LLN-SYNTAX-LEGACY-002 (warning)
with effects [...]                  — hard error LLN-SYNTAX-LEGACY-001
else if                             — hard error LLN-SYNTAX-010
top-level fn
fn effects clauses
assignment expressions
++ / --
ternary ?:
pipeline operator |>
```

## Return Type Syntax

Both `->` and `:` are accepted as return-type separators. No diagnostic is
emitted for either form. `:` is the **modern preferred form**. Formatters may
normalise to either, but new code should use `:`.

```ebnf
(* Accepted forms — both valid, no diagnostic; ':' is modern preferred *)
flow_decl = [ flow_qualifier ] , "flow" , identifier ,
            "(" , [ param_list ] , ")" , ( "->" | ":" ) , type_ref ,
            { flow_clause } , block ;
```

## Top-Level Public Result Types

The preferred pattern for flows with rich return types is to declare the result
type as a top-level `type` declaration rather than inline in the signature or in
`contract.types`:

```ebnf
(* Preferred — top-level public result type *)
type_decl = "type" , type_identifier , "=" , type_ref ;

(* Examples:
   type AuditPatientResult = Result<Response, AuditError>
   type CreateOrderResult  = Result<Response, ApiError>

   These are declared at the compilation unit level so they are visible to
   routes, tests, and other flows without importing contract internals. *)
```

The `contract.types {}` form (flow-local aliases) remains valid but is preferred
only when the result type is genuinely private to a single flow.

## `unsafe let` at the Flow Boundary

`unsafe let` marks variables that originate from raw HTTP / external input at the
flow boundary. The binding carries `unsafe` value-state and requires a validation
gate before it can be passed to a governed sink.

```ebnf
(* From the binding_stmt production — 'unsafe let' is the boundary form *)
binding_stmt = binding_prefix , identifier , [ ":" , type_ref ] , "=" , expression ;
binding_prefix = "unsafe" , ( "let" | "mut" ) | ... ;

(* Canonical usage:
   unsafe let rawId: String = request.params.patientId
   safe   mut rawId         = validate.uuid(rawId)?
*)
```

## Phase 41 Syntax Additions (summary)

The following were formalised or clarified in Phase 41:

| Feature | Rule |
|---|---|
| `:` return type | Modern preferred form; `->` still accepted |
| Inline contract | `contract {}` may appear as first item in flow body `{}` |
| `when` guard arms | `when expr => body` in `match` expressions |
| Integer/string literal arms | `200 => return "ok"` in `match` expressions |
| `effects {}` optional | Omission = pure (no effects declared) |
| Top-level result types | Preferred over `contract.types {}` for public flows |
| No `else if` | Hard error LLN-SYNTAX-010; use `match` or sequential `if` |
| `unsafe let` boundary form | Marks raw HTTP/request input at flow entry |

